'''Kubotsu Ōji''' ('''くぼつおうじ''') is the first of the {{ill|Kumano Gongen|ja|熊野権現|qq=draft}}'s {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|ja|熊野九十九王子|qq=draft}} shrines. It was located near the {{ill|Hachikenya Boat Dock|ja|八軒家船着場|qq=draft}} in the {{ill|Tenmabashi|ja|天満橋|qq=draft}} area of {{ill|Chūō-ku, Osaka|ja|中央区 (大阪市)|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka City|ja|大阪市|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft}}. Today, the site is marked by the {{ill|Ikasuri Shrine|ja|坐摩神社|qq=draft}} {{nihongo|Temporary Shrine|行宮}}.
Later, Kubotsu Ōji was enshrined as {{ill|Kumano Shrine|ja|熊野神社|qq=draft}} near the western gate of {{ill|Shitennō-ji|ja|四天王寺|qq=draft}}. On February 10, {{ill|1915|ja|1915th year|qq=draft}} (Taishō 4), it was relocated to {{ill|Horikoshi Shrine|ja|堀越神社|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Horikoshi Town|ja|堀越町|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tennoji-ku, Osaka|ja|天王寺区|qq=draft}}, where it is now a subordinate shrine known as "Kumano Daiichi Ōji Shrine" (熊野第一王子社).
The {{ill|Ikasuri Shrine|ja|坐摩神社|qq=draft}} originally stood at this location but was moved to {{ill|Kyūtarō-machi, Osaka|ja|久太郎町|qq=draft}} in Chūō-ku during the construction of {{ill|Osaka Castle|ja|大阪城|qq=draft}}. Many retired emperors (*jōkō*) who undertook the {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野御幸|qq=draft}} also visited this site.
== Nearest Stations == * '''Ikasuri Shrine Temporary Shrine:''' {{ill|Keihan Electric Railway|ja|京阪電気鉄道|qq=draft}} / {{ill|Osaka Metro Tanimachi Line|ja|Osaka Metro谷町線|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Temmabashi Station|ja|天満橋駅|qq=draft}} * '''Ikasuri Shrine:''' {{ill|Osaka Metro Midosuji Line|ja|Osaka Metro御堂筋線|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Hommachi Station|ja|本町駅|qq=draft}} * '''Horikoshi Shrine:''' {{ill|JR West|ja|西日本旅客鉄道|qq=draft}} – {{ill|Tennoji Station|ja|天王寺駅|qq=draft}}
